Probe

Target IP: 10.10.229.90
Challenge Description: Sometimes all you know against a target is an IP address. Can you complete the challenge and conduct an in-depth probe on the target?

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.229.90 -p- shows there are eight TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above. Time to perform an aggressive port scan against these TCP ports to identify the services.

I performed an aggressive port scan against the eight TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.229.90 -p 22,80,443,1338,1443,1883,8000,9007 and obtained the result shown above. Most applications seem to be HTTP. The HTTP application on the standard port seems to be running lighttpd. There is an interesting FTP application on port 1338. And the target machine seems to be running Apache 2.4.41. The hostname dev.probe.thm also appears multiple times; therefore, I will add this hostname inside my /etc/hosts file.


After inserting the hostname inside my /etc/hosts file, I browsed to https://dev.probe.thm. Viewing the certificate contains the juicy information shown above. The email probe@probe.thm seems interesting.

Port 1443: HTTP

This port is interesting as it displays the development build information, such as the PHP version, hostname, etc, as shown above. The PHP extension build the target machine is running is API20190902,NTS, as shown above.

Port 8000: HTTP

Performing a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://dev.probe.thm:8000/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x html,php,txt shows the target machine is running phpmyadmin. There is also another directory called /contactus, as shown above. Browsing to this page contains the flag THM{CONTACT_US_1100}.

Port 9007: HTTPs

This port serves the WordPress application. The target machine seems to be running Wordpress as the CMS. The application version is 6.2.2, as shown above.

┌──(kali㉿kali)-[~/Desktop/Lab-Resource/Completed/Probe]

Doing a basic wpscan using the command wpscan --url https://dev.probe.thm:9007/ --enumerate u --disable-tls-checks against the target machine returns the result shown above. There is a user called joomla. Running nikto against this port gives another flag. The command nikto -u https://dev.probe.thm:9007 returns another flag which is the filename license.txt. GG. Overall this challenge was simple, but effective.
